{"type":"message","id":"dbdc23b7","parentId":"fbfffdca","timestamp":"2026-04-05T19:06:26.331Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The timestamp 1775338200 corresponds to April 4, 2026 at 21:30 UTC. That's yesterday evening. The health report says last run was March 31, but the cron state shows April 4? There's a discrepancy. Let's check the memory_review last run timestamp from the state file: \"2026-03-31T12:38:00Z\". That's March 31 at 12:38 UTC. That is definitely before April 4. So the cron state's lastRunAtMs might not be the same as the actual last successful run? The health monitor reads the heartbeat-state.json, not the cron state. So the health monitor is using the state file timestamps.\n\nSo the memory_review hasn't updated the state since March 31. The nightly-memory-review cron job might be failing to complete, or it might be running but not updating the state file (the heartbeart-state-manager is only run by the agent during heartbeat polls, not by that cron). Actually, the nightly-memory-review cron job does not call update_state.py. It's not a heartbeat check; it's a separate cron job that does its own memory review. So the memory_review field in heartbeat-state.json is updated only when the heartbeat routine performs a memory review check? Wait: In HEARTBEAT.md, one of the tasks is \"Memory review: Check memory files for consistency, backfill daily notes, update MEMORY.md as needed.\" That's part of the heartbeat routine, not the nightly cron job. Actually there are two things: The heartbeat does a periodic check (every 30 min) that includes memory review. And there is also a separate cron job called \"nightly-memory-review\" that does a more thorough review at 3 AM. Both might update the heartbeat state? In the heartbeat routine, after doing the memory review task, it calls update_state.py with --field memory_review. The nightly cron job, however, does not have that step; it's a separate agent turn that does its own memory curation and then pushes to GitHub. But the health monitor expects the memory_review field to be updated. If the nightly cron runs, it would do a memory review but not update the heartbeat state. That would cause the health monitor to think memory_review is stale even though the nightly job succeeded. But the health monitor expects the heartbeat check to have run. The memory_review field is supposed to be updated by the heartbeat routine's memory review task, not by the nightly cron. The nightly cron is a separate job that does weekly memory curation. The health monitor thresholds: memory_review threshold is 1800 minutes (30 hours). The heartbeat runs every 30 min during active hours, so it should update that field at least every 30 min if it includes memory review in every heartbeat. But maybe the heartbeat does memory review less frequently? Let's look at the HEARTBEAT.md checklist: It includes \"Memory review: Check memory files for consistency, backfill daily notes, update MEMORY.md as needed.\" That appears to be part of every heartbeat? That would be heavy. Possibly it's not meant to run every 30 min; maybe it's a separate check? But the heartbeat-state-manager script is called at the end with fields: heartbeat_run, and optionally group_message, nemesis_ping, git_push, memory_review depending on what was done. So the memory_review field is updated only if a memory review was performed during that heartbeat. So if the heartbeat hasn't been running, it won't update.\n\nNow, the fact that group_message and nemesis_ping haven't updated for 2.3 days suggests the heartbeat hasn't been running at all during that period. Why? Perhaps the agent hasn't had an active session. Since the gateway's heartbeat target is \"last\", it sends to the last active session. If there hasn't been any session activity for >2 days, there is no active session to send to, so no heartbeat polls are sent. That would explain the staleness. But we have a session now, so after this session ends, maybe the heartbeat will resume? Actually, the heartbeat is tied to a session. As long as the session is active (i.e., the agent is not idle beyond the reset idle threshold), the gateway will send periodic polls to that session. The session reset config: direct messages have idleMinutes: 240 (4 hours). So if there's no activity in a direct session for 4 hours, the session resets (closes). Once the session is reset, the \"last\" target might point to an old closed session? Or perhaps the gateway creates a new session when a new message arrives. So the heartbeat will only run during an active session. Since we have an active session now (this conversation), heartbeats should be sent every 30 min during active hours. But the health monitor report showed that the last group_message and nemesis_ping were 2.3 days ago, meaning there hasn't been an active session since then. But we clearly have a session now. Possibly the session was just created now by this \"/new\" command. So before this, there was no active session for days. That explains why those fields are stale: no heartbeat because no session existed. That's actually okay. The health monitor is designed to alert if heartbeats stop while a session is expected to be active. But it might not account for periods of inactivity when no session exists. However, the heartbeat-health-monitor cron runs independently and assumes state should be fresh. We might need to adjust the interpretation or manually reset those fields now that a new session is active.\n\nBut the cron jobs: github-backup and nightly-memory-review are separate and should run regardless of agent sessions, because they spawn isolated sessions. They have been failing to run. Let's check their lastRunAtMs from cron state: For github-backup, lastRunAtMs: 1775412080669. Let's convert that.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_9880719ad3c64a8899588876","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"date -d @1775412080 -u"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"kilocode","model":"stepfun/step-3.5-flash:free","usage":{"input":1215,"output":2690,"cacheRead":38528,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":42433,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775415962359,"responseId":"gen-1775415963-LG2p49qcAuimjYZDFvFl"}}
