{"type":"message","id":"6728c120","parentId":"4a8c39f5","timestamp":"2026-04-05T19:07:40.761Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So the health monitor ran at 19:00:38 UTC, which is just about 30 seconds before the current time (19:01). That means it just sent the alert. It's running fine.\n\nNow the plan.\n\nI should also consider: Could there be a misconfiguration that prevented heartbeats from running even when sessions were active? Possibly but not indicated.\n\nOne more thing: The heartbeat-state.json file is being written by the update_state.py script. The agent should call it via exec. That script might have failed due to permission issues? But it's just writing to a file in the workspace; should be fine.\n\nMaybe the agent never computed that it needed to update those fields because the heartbeat tasks were not part of the heartbeat routine. Let's check what the heartbeat routine actually does. The HEARTBEAT.md file is a skill that tells the agent what to do. It may be that the agent is not loading that file or not following it correctly. But that skill is part of the agent's default behavior? Actually, the agent has a skill for heartbeat? Not necessarily; the HEARTBEAT.md is a file in the workspace that the agent is supposed to read and follow when it receives a heartbeat poll. The agent's system prompt may instruct it to follow HEARTBEAT.md when a heartbeat occurs. That is standard OpenClaw behavior: The system sends a heartbeat event, and the agent must read the HEARTBEAT.md file and perform the tasks, then call update_state.py. So if the agent was never loaded with that file or didn't act, it might ignore heartbeats. But that seems unlikely because it's part of the core skills.\n\nMaybe the agent didn't have the skill installed? Actually, the heartbeat-state-manager is a skill in the workspace: `skills/heartbeat-state-manager`. The HEARTBEAT.md is in the workspace root. That skill might be automatically loaded? Not sure.\n\nAnyway, we need to produce a plan.\n\nLet's also check the cron state for the failing cron jobs to see if they actually succeeded. The github-backup job's lastRunStatus is \"ok\". So it ran successfully. The nightly-memory-review's lastRunStatus is \"ok\". So they succeeded. So the alerts are about heartbeat state only.\n\nThus, the issue is solely the heartbeat state being stale because no active session for days. The fix: Create an active session (we have now), and ensure heartbeat routine updates state. Perhaps we also need to manually run the update_state to reset the timestamps to avoid immediate further alerts, but that's not strictly necessary; after the next heartbeat, the fields will update. But if the next heartbeat is many hours away (07:00 IST), the health monitor will run again at 20:00 UTC (01:30 IST?) Actually it runs hourly. The next hour at 20:00 UTC (01:30 IST) will still be outside active hours. At that time, the state will still be stale because no heartbeat will have occurred yet (since still outside active hours). That would trigger another alert. To avoid that, we could either manually update state now, or adjust health monitor thresholds (not ideal), or wait until after 07:00 IST when the first heartbeat occurs and then state becomes fresh. But the health monitor runs hourly, so at 20:00 UTC, 21:00 UTC, etc., it would still see stale state until 07:30 IST maybe. That could cause multiple alerts. So it's better to manually reset state now to avoid spam.\n\nThus, I'll include a step to manually update state now.\n\nBut also we need to verify that the heartbeat routine will actually work when the first heartbeat arrives. We could even simulate a heartbeat manually: The gateway might have a way to send a heartbeat event to the agent. Could use `openclaw gateway call`? Not sure. Possibly there's a system event that can be sent. But maybe simpler: we can manually run the heartbeat tasks ourselves as a one-off to ensure they work and update state. That would be a good test.\n\nIn the HEARTBEAT.md, the tasks are:\n\n- Time check first: Get current IST time.\n- Pending tasks: Check if Nemesis mentioned pending tasks.\n- Group vibes: Check if it's been 3+ hours since last group message; if so, send something relevant.\n- Group supervision: Read last 10 group messages; if Nexa said something wrong, send correction.\n- Ping Nemesis: Check if it's been 4+ hours since last DM; if so, send relevant alert.\n- Group memory: Update GROUP.md if significant activity.\n- Silent exit if nothing.\n\nAnd finally: persist state.\n\nSo we could manually simulate some of those tasks. But it's easier to manually call update_state for the fields we care about.\n\nI think the plan should be:\n\n**Analysis**:\n- The critical alerts are from the heartbeat-health-monitor cron which checks the heartbeat-state.json file.\n- The timestamps in that file are stale because the regular heartbeat polls haven't been occurring. Heartbeat polls are only sent when there is an active agent session. There hasn't been an active session for ~2.3 days (as indicated by the timestamps). The cron jobs (github-backup, nightly-memory-review) are actually running fine (confirmed by cron list). The alert is about the heartbeat state, not about those cron jobs themselves.\n- Since we just started a new session, heartbeats will resume automatically during active hours (7 AM - 11 PM IST). However, the next heartbeat won't occur until at least 7:30 AM IST (the first 30-minute interval after 7:00). Until then, the state will remain stale, and the hourly health monitor will keep sending alerts.\n\n**Plan**:\n1. **Immediate mitigation**: Manually update the heartbeat state timestamps to now to prevent further alerts until the first natural heartbeat occurs.\n   - Run: `python3 ~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/heartbeat-state-manager/scripts/update_state.py --field heartbeat_run --field group_message --field nemesis_ping --field git_push --field memory_review`\n   - This will set all monitored fields to current UTC time, which is within thresholds.\n\n2. **Verification of heartbeat functionality**: After the next active heartbeat window (tomorrow morning), check that the state file is automatically updated. Also confirm that the agent can actually execute the state update (i.e., the update_state.py script is callable and has write permissions). Optionally, we can manually trigger a heartbeat simulation now to test: call the agent with a heartbeat event? Not straightforward; but we can wait.\n\n3. **Cron job verification**: Even though they appear healthy, manually run each cron job to confirm they succeed without errors:\n   - Use `openclaw cron run --jobId <id>` for github-backup and nightly-memory-review.\n   - Check outputs for errors. If any fail, investigate.\n\n4. **Long-term**: Ensure that sessions are periodically active so heartbeats continue. The direct message session will stay alive for 4 hours after the last activity. We can interact periodically or rely on new messages. This is normal.\n\n5. **Optional**: Adjust the heartbeat health monitor thresholds to be more tolerant of expected downtime (e.g., if no session exists). But that's a code change; not needed unless alerts persist despite active sessions.\n\nI'll also include a note that the health monitor's `memory_review`, `git_push`, `group_message`, `nemesis_ping` are heartbeat task fields, not cron job statuses. The actual cron jobs are fine.\n\nNow I'll produce the final answer.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Alright, here's the diagnosis and fix plan.\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe Heartbeat Health Monitor is complaining because the **heartbeat state file** (`memory/heartbeat-state.json`) is stale. That file is only updated when the agent receives and processes a **heartbeat poll** from the gateway. Heartbeat polls are only sent while an agent session is active. There hasn’t been an active session for ~2.3 days, so the state never updated. The cron jobs themselves (`github-backup`, `nightly-memory-review`) are actually running fine – their own timestamps are recent.\n\n## What’s actually broken vs false alarm\n\n- **False alarm**: The cron jobs are healthy (`github-backup` ran ~1h ago, `nightly-memory-review` ran yesterday).\n- **Real but expected**: Heartbeat stopped because no session existed. Now that we have a session, heartbeats will resume during active hours (7 AM–11 PM IST).\n\n## Plan\n\n### 1. Immediate — silence further alerts\nManually refresh the heartbeat state now so the next hourly health check sees fresh timestamps:\n\n```bash\npython3 ~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/heartbeat-state-manager/scripts/update_state.py \\\n  --field heartbeat_run \\\n  --field group_message \\\n  --field nemesis_ping \\\n  --field git_push \\\n  --field memory_review\n```\n\n### 2. Verify heartbeat will run automatically\n- The gateway sends a heartbeat every 30 min between 7 AM–11 PM IST to the current session.\n- After 7:30 AM IST tomorrow, check `memory/heartbeat-state.json`; the timestamps should have moved forward.\n- The hourly `heartbeat-health-monitor` cron will then report healthy.\n\n### 3. Spot-check cron job outputs\nTo be thorough, manually trigger the two cron jobs that the health monitor indirectly referenced:\n\n```bash\n# Find job IDs from earlier list\nopenclaw cron run --jobId <github-backup-id> --runMode force\nopenclaw cron run --jobId <nightly-memory-review-id> --runMode force\n```\n\nLook for errors. If they succeed, you’ll see “NO_REPLY” or a success message.\n\n### 4. Long-term\n- Nothing else needed; as long as you interact within the 4-hour direct-session idle window, heartbeats will keep running.\n- If you expect long idle periods, consider lowering the heartbeat health thresholds in `skills/heartbeat-state-manager/scripts/heartbeat_health_cron.py` (optional).\n\nWant me to run step 1 now and verify step 3?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"kilocode","model":"stepfun/ste