{"type":"message","id":"e4879958","parentId":"b1367130","timestamp":"2026-04-06T08:46:49.473Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"We need to check the group messages to see if there are any that I should have responded to. Looking at the cron list, I see the github-backup job has an error: rate limit exceeded. That's likely the API limit error the user is referring to.\n\nThe error message is: \"⚠️ Rate limit exceeded: limit_rpm/stepfun/step-3.5-flash/8a9f6e11-a2df-4ac5-90c5-e6c7ef96955c. High demand for stepfun/step-3.5-flash:free on OpenRouter - limited to 50 requests per minute. Please retry shortly.\"\n\nThis is happening in the github-backup cron job, which tries to do a web search (using the model) to summarize AI news. The web search is hitting the rate limit.\n\nBut the user said \"check the group mssgs, due to api limit error u were not able to respond properly\". This suggests that there was a group message that I should have responded to, but I couldn't because of the API limit error.\n\nHowever, the github-backup cron job sends its output via DM to Nemesis (target=7924461837), not to the group. The delivery mode is \"none\" and channel=\"last\", to=7924461837. So it's not sending to the group.\n\nBut there's also the \"ai-news-digest\" cron job which does send to Nemesis via DM as well (delivery mode announce, channel=telegram, target=7924461837). That one might also be hitting rate limits? Let me check its status: it shows lastRunStatus: ok, lastDeliveryStatus: delivered. So it's working fine.\n\nThe issue might be that when I tried to respond to something in the group chat (maybe a mention or a question), I hit the API limit and couldn't generate a proper response. But looking at the session history, I see that I've been responding in the direct session with Nemesis. I don't see any group session in the sessions_list output - only one session: the direct one with Nemesis.\n\nSo maybe there were no group messages that required a response. Or perhaps the user is referring to the fact that the heartbeat health monitor cron job was failing due to API limits? Let me check that: the heartbeat-health-monitor job shows lastRunStatus: ok, lastDeliveryStatus: delivered. It ran successfully.\n\nActually, looking back at the cron health monitor output from earlier (before the git pull), I saw: \"• heartbeat-health-monitor (warning) - 1 consecutive error(s) - OpenRouter API limit exceeded\". That was from an earlier run. But now it shows consecutiveErrors: 0 and lastRunStatus: ok. So it's currently healthy.\n\nThe github-backup job is the one with the current error.\n\nBut the user's message is: \"check the group mssgs, due to api limit error u were not able to respond properly\". This is ambiguous. It could mean:\n1. There were group messages that I should have responded to, but I couldn't due to API limit error.\n2. The API limit error prevented me from responding properly in general (maybe in DM or group).\n3. They want me to check the group messages to see if there's anything I missed.\n\nGiven that they said \"check the group mssgs\", I should look at recent group messages to see if there are any unread or pending responses.\n\nBut I don't have a direct way to fetch group chat history unless there's a session for it. However, I can check if there are any pending tasks or if the GROUP.md needs updating based on recent group activity.\n\nLooking at GROUP.md, the \"Current Group Lore & Active Context\" section was last updated with the feminine communication tip series started on April 5. That's from the daily cron job. There might be more recent group activity that's not reflected in GROUP.md.\n\nSince I can't directly fetch group message history, I should ask the user if there's something specific they want me to check, or I can just acknowledge and say I'll keep an eye on the group.\n\nActually, I recall that in the AGENTS.md, there's a section about group chats: \"You have access to your human's stuff. That doesn't mean you *share* their stuff. In groups, you're a participant — not their voice, not their proxy. Think before you speak.\"\n\nAnd: \"Respond when: Directly mentioned or asked a question... Stay silent when: It's just casual banter between humans...\"\n\nSo unless I was @mentioned or asked a question in the group, I shouldn't have responded anyway.\n\nMaybe the user is just letting me know that there was an API limit error that affected my ability to respond, and they want me to be aware of it.\n\nLet me check if there were any recent @mentions or messages that required a response. Since I can't fetch group history directly, I'll have to rely on the user to tell me if there was something specific.\n\nAlternatively, I can check the GROUP.md for any updates that might have come from group interactions that I missed.\n\nBut the GROUP.md seems to be manually updated by me when I notice something important. The last update was about the feminine communication tip series.\n\nGiven the ambiguity, I'll respond by acknowledging that I saw the API limit error in the github-backup cron, and that I'm monitoring the situation. I'll also say that I'll respond appropriately if I'm mentioned or asked a question in the group.\n\nActually, let me first check if there's a way to get recent group messages. I recall that in the message tool, there might be a way to get history for a chat. Let me look at the message tool schema again... Actually, I don't see a \"get\" action. There's \"send\", \"poll\", \"react\", \"delete\", \"edit\", \"topic-create\", \"topic-edit\". No \"get\" or \"history\".\n\nHowever, I can use the sessions tool if there's a session for the group chat. Let me check if there's a session for the group by looking at the sessions more carefully. The sessions_list output only showed one session. But maybe there are more if I don't limit it? Let me increase the limit.\n\nActually, I can check the GROUP.md for any recent updates that might indicate I missed something. Or I can just ask the user if they want me to respond to something specific in the group.\n\nGiven the time, I'll provide a helpful response: acknowledge the API limit issue, say I'm monitoring, and offer to check for any specific group messages they want me to address.\n\nBut wait, the user's message is: \"check the group mssgs, due to api limit error u were not able to respond properly\". This sounds like they're asking me to check the group messages. So I should attempt to do that.\n\nSince I can't directly fetch group history, I'll explain the limitation and suggest alternatives.\n\nLet me craft a response: I'll say that I don't have direct access to fetch group message history, but I can check GROUP.md for context, and if they want me to respond to something specific in the group, they should let me know what it was or @mention me.\n\nActually, I just remembered: I can use the `message` tool with action to send a message to the group to ask if there's anything I missed, but that seems silly.\n\nBetter approach: Since the user is asking me to check the group messages, and I can't do that directly, I'll explain the limitation and offer to help in other ways.\n\nBut let me first check if there's a session for the group that I missed. Let me run sessions_list without a limit or with a higher limit.\n\nActually, let me try to get all sessions.\n<tool_call>\n<function=sessions_list>\n<parameter=limit>\n100\n</parameter>\n</function>\n</tool_call>\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"We need to check the group messages to see if there are any that I should have responded to. Looking at the cron list, I see the github-backup job has an error: rate limit exceeded. That's likely the API limit error the user is referring to.\n\nThe error message is: \"⚠️ Rate limit exceeded: limit_rpm/stepfun/step-3.5-flash/8a9f6e11-a2df-4ac5-90c5-e6c7ef96955c. High demand for stepfun/step-3.5-flash:free on OpenRouter - limited to 50 requests per minute. Please retry shortly.\"\n\nThis is happening in the github-backup cron job, which tries to do a web search (using the model) to summarize AI news. The web search is hitting the rate limit.\n\nBut the user said \"check the group mssgs, due to api limit error u were not able to respond properly\". This suggests that there was a group message that I should have responded to, but I couldn't because of the API limit error.\n\nHowever, the github-backup cron job sends its output via DM to Nemesis (target=7924461837), not to the group. The delivery mode is \"none\" and channel=\"last\", to=7924461837. So it's not sending to the group.\n\nBut there's also the \"ai-news-digest\" cron job which does send to Nemesis via DM as well (delivery mode announce, channel=telegram, target=7924461837). That one might also be hitting rate limits? Let me check its status: it shows lastRunStatus: ok, lastDeliveryStatus: delivered. So it's working fine.\n\nThe issue might be that when I tried to respond to something in the group chat (maybe a mention or a question), I hit the API limit and couldn't generate a proper response. But looking at the session history, I see that I've been responding in the direct session with Nemesis. I don't see any group session in the sessions_list output - only one session: the direct one with Nemesis.\n\nSo maybe there were no group messages that required a response. Or perhaps the user is referring to the fact that the heartbeat health monitor cron job was failing due to API limits? Let me check that: the heartbeat-health-monitor job shows lastRunStatus: ok, lastDeliveryStatus: delivered. It ran successfully.\n\nActually, looking back at the cron health monitor output from earlier (before the git pull), I saw: \"• heartbeat-health-monitor (warning) - 1 consecutive error(s) - OpenRouter API limit exceeded\". That was from an earlier run. But now it shows consecutiveErrors: 0 and lastRunStatus: ok. So it's currently healthy.\n\nThe github-bac